          <h2 style="             
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 500;
              margin-top: 2px !important;">What is the Laffer Curve?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.longandshort.com/email/images/arthur-laffer-economist-curves.png" alt="Economist Arthur Laffer shows off his curves" href="https://www.longandshort.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Economist Arthur Laffer shows off his curves. Credits: AP</p>
        </mj-text> 
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">The Laffer Curve is an economic concept that shows the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #6b705c; color: black;" href="https://link.longandshort.com/ls-01-03-2025-f1-14-relationship-between-tax-rates-and-government-revenue?source=website" target="_blank">relationship between tax rates and government revenue</a>. It suggests that increasing taxes doesn’t always mean the government will collect more money. Instead, there is a point where higher tax rates reduce tax revenue.</p>  

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span>If tax rates are too low, the government doesn’t collect enough money.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span>If tax rates are too high, people and businesses may stop working as hard, avoid taxes, or even move their money elsewhere to avoid paying. This leads to less tax revenue.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5;"><span style="font-size:20px; padding-right:5px;">→</span>The Curve suggests that there is an optimal tax rate where government revenue is maximized.</p>

          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>Example:</strong>
          If a country taxes income at 10%, revenue is low. Raising it to 30% increases revenue as people still work and pay taxes. But at 80%, many may work less, evade taxes, or move abroad, reducing revenue. This shows that overly high taxes can backfire.

          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
